ce:section.ce:para:
The first stage of low power ultrasonication of graphite in NMP (<12 h) fractured large flakes into fragments [31], with a broad micron-sized distribution spreading into sub-micron size scales, where thinner flakes may have fragmented into these smaller fragments [32], but here with negligible proportion below 300 nm (hydrodynamic) size, even after 24 h (
                           Supplementary Section 1, Figure S1
                        ). Subsequent ultrasonication to 36 h moved the major size distribution further down into the sub-micron region, but with only a minor proportion around 100 nm size (
                           Figure S1
                        ). Oxidation of carbon–carbon bonds broken in fragmentation may assist exfoliation of smaller fragments [16]. From 48 h, greater proportions of small nanosheets accumulated and reached useful levels after 60 h of ultrasonication. Erosion of small fragments broken from the edge of larger fragments likely contributed from 36 to 60 h and would dominate after 100 h [31]. Although more extensive ultrasonication would increase the yield of very small 0D dots, we also sought here the isolation of small 1-2LG nanosheets at the earlier stages, with possible different sonochemical modifications, as they transitioned into photoluminescent nanosheets.

Low power ultrasonication for 60 h produced the usual grey dispersion (Supplementary Figure S2
                        ), when low speed centrifugation removed remaining graphitic flakes and left typical (Supplementary Figure S3
                        ) colloidal multi-layer and few-layer graphene dispersions [16,17]. Stepwise increases in low-speed centrifugation only shifted the broad and overlapping hydrodynamic size distributions to a lower mean size. However, with high-speed centrifugation up to 58,000 g, we harvested a size distribution with less overlap down to 25 nm (
                        Supplementary Figure S3
                        ). Consequently, we removed graphitic and larger multi-layer graphene flakes at 3,200 g, before harvesting grey-black larger (∼75 nm) FLG nanosheets (LG) at 17,000g and smaller (∼25 nm) 1-2LG nanosheets by high-speed centrifugation at 58,000g.

As expected, larger FLG (LG) nanosheets, lacking hydrogens, showed no proton (1H) NMR signals [24], but the smaller 1-2LG nanosheets and dots showed rich 1H NMR regions (Fig. 4 left). Strikingly, both large and small nanosheets, as well as dots had rich 13C NMR spectra, thus signifying the presence of carbon atoms adjacent to nitrogen-containing functionalities in particular, and (to a lesser extent) oxygen-containing functional groups (Fig. 4 right). We found that the bulk of these modifications were likely to originate directly from sonochemical N and O addition reactions during exfoliation, gained by close proximity to highly-reactive N⋅ and O⋅ gas radicals and/or highly-energetic N and O atoms after scission diatomic N2 and O2 from imploding air bubbles, with possible cumulative OH⋅ radical attack from water vapour, rather than from sonochemical polymerisation of NMP [24], or from secondary organic modifications from the associated breakdown products of NMP (see later Section 3.2.6 with 
                              Figures S18 and S19
                           ).

The high atomic percentage of sp2 C = C of LG (87.1 %) and dialysed nanosheets (highest at 75.6 % for the thicker DF1, see (Supplementary Figure S10

                           h) indicated that most of the carbon atoms remained arranged in honeycomb lattices, also confirmed by HR-TEM (see Fig. 2 
                           a above). The high-resolution N 1s spectra of small black 1-2LG RF1 and smaller nanosheets (Supplementary Figure S11
                           ) revealed the existence of predominantly graphitic (C)3-N at 399.0 eV, with some C-N=C at 400.2 eV mostly in small 1-2LG (RF1), and otherwise some N–H of amides at 397.1 eV in the smaller nanosheets and dots. The deconvolution of the high-resolution O 1s spectra (
                              Figure S12
                           ) showed three components corresponding to C=O at 530.0 eV, C-O at 531.9 eV and adsorbed water on the surface at 533.9 eV.

During ultrasonication, some of the exfoliated FLG nanosheets were fragmented into smaller-sized 1–2 layer graphene (1-2LG) nanosheets with a greater proportion of chemically-active edges [19,40]. Cavitation drives sonochemistry of all solvents and their dissolved gases. The above chemical characterisations all indicated that dissolved gases provided the predominant sonochemical modifications at the transition into photoluminescence. Even normally-inert noble gases become ionised and participate in the degradation of water and other molecules [41]. The energies of bubble implosion are sufficient for cleavage of covalent bonds, which are capable of producing different reactive species of NMP, facilitating synolysis of water vapour molecules into hydrogen and hydroxyl radicals, as well as the ionisation of dissolved molecular oxygen and nitrogen on implosion of gas cavitation bubbles. Consequently, sonication of graphite in water oxidises graphene flakes with chemical attachment of oxygen species [16]. Sonication in organic solvents, including NMP, produces reactive degradation products [14], which may chemically attach to the edges of exfoliated graphene. Here, we observed nitrogen modifications, including in the larger photoluminescent fragments, and even the smaller black 1-2LG (RF1) was modified with nitrogen (Supplementary Figure S11
                           ). However, predominantly individual N atoms were introduced, thus suggesting that dissolved nitrogen from air was a ready source of reactive nitrogen atoms and radicals to nitrogenate graphene, rather than breakdown products of NMP [16], presumably related to its relatively low vapor pressure. Further details with possible reaction schemes are offered in Supplementary materials (Section 9. Ultrasonically-assisted N-doping of graphene materials). Atomic nitrogen and/or radical N⋅ additions can explain the pyridine-like structures and graphitic nitrogen and amines present (Figs. 4, 5 
                           b and Supplementary Figure S11
                           ), with possible engagement of hydrogen radicals (from water vapour, Supplementary Figure S16
                           ). Sonochemical breakdown products of NMP (Supplementary Figure S17
                           ) may also have progressive secondary contribution in small nanosheets and dots to generate amides and tertiary amines (Supplementary Figure S18
                           ). Similarly, the predominant O atom additions (Figs. 4, 5 
                           b and Supplementary Figure S12
                           ) are likely from atomic O and O⋅ radical attack. H⋅ and OH⋅ radicals generated from water vapour in air also progressively contributed in secondary modification of the small nanosheets and dots.

Indeed, the PL emission spectra of this least-modified RF2 isolate excited at 340 nm (Fig. 6 
                           g) had an emission peak centred at 428 nm with a red-shifted shoulder extending towards 500 nm, suggestive of a red shift contribution from assembly even in dilute solution. The emission maximum for RF2 centred at 428 nm, while shifted a few nm to 425 nm for other more modified nanosheets of different sizes (RF3, DF1 and DF2). However, the blue shift in PL emission extended much further down to 404 nm for the most modified and much smaller 1–2 nm 0D dot-like isolate (DF3). This blue shift of the emission spectra (with 24 nm difference between the most modified DF3 and least modified RF2) appears attributable to greater modification, as well as to smaller size. The presence of N and O atoms with strong electron affinity in the nanosheets led to the blue shift of PL spectra with modification of the nanosheets [27,52]. As the smallest nanosheet isolate (DF3) had the highest content of N- and O-containing functional groups, its blue shift was greater than that of the other isolates, but this could be influenced by size too. The band-gap energies from Tauc plots derived from UV spectra (Supplementary Figure S13

                           ) indicated how the size-related quantum confinement effect could alter PL. The increased band-gap energy from the largest-sized isolate of 4.086 eV to the smallest nanosheet of 5.670 eV (Supplementary Table S2
                           ) suggests that the quantum confinement effect could also have contributed to the larger PL emission of these small 1–2 nm dot-like nanosheets.
